Pair together, seen while recording was made. For most of the recording the first bird is likely the male (lower pitched voice) a few times alone then the females call is added. There is a series of calls near the middle of the recording where the male and female overlap, male first then female with a slight overlap of the beginning of the female with the end of the male's vocalization. These are the "guard calls" of the species, indicating that they were aroused, probably by my presence, however they had been calling before there was a direct line-of-sight view. The birds were across a pond/mudflat approximately 100 to 150 m away.

Last of three recordings from 26 March 2014 between 8:05-8:20pm, from the north end of the Godown Road Park (Dog Park) on the east side of the OSU Airport area off Godown Rd, Columbus, OH.  There were multiple birds present and calling/displaying, but the recordings focused on one individual "peent"calling from the ground, then flying off giving twittering areal display calls before (in this recording) returning to the same site (It lands around 0:20 then resumes "peent"ing).  Shortly after this, around 1:10, a Great Horned Owl flew over, silencing all but one distant bird for at least the next 10 minutes.  Habitat: Mixed brush, sparse trees and heavily impacted grassland mix.
Recording made using a Sennheiser ME67 shotgun mic and a Sony Hi-MD recorder, model MZ-RH910 and cleaned up using Audacity: High Pass filter (2k, 5q, 12db) and noise removal.  
WAV version at https://soundcloud.com/paul-j-hurtado/american-woodcock-3-3.

Small edits were made to the original recording including noise reduction, fade in/out, and amplification. No splitting or shortening of intervals. The owls were recorded for more than one hour but this segment was selected as it had the least background noise to contend with. Rural habitat; large open fields with rolling / varied topography; a creek is surrounded by large mature trees (pine, oak, birch, maple) and meanders through the countryside. The owls (two males and one female) were heard calling back and forth. One of the males flew in and perched 50 ft. above the recorder. These are resident Great Horned Owls and we have witnessed the pair using the dead trees on the opposite side of our street as a perch over the past several years. Hearing a second male encroaching, the male perched above the recorder took flight in the direction of the other male and disappeared into the night. Shortly after the male departed, the female flew in and landed in the same tree and began calling. This is the female segment of the recording.

Recording of a red-morph eastern screech owl calling from a mature sycamore tree right around sunset. Only minor adjustments were made to the recording, including noise reduction and minor amplification; no splits or cuts were made. Calls continued in roughly one-minute intervals for more than 30 minutes. A running creek surrounds vast quantities of open fields/  farmland. Mature trees flank the creek on both sides. This owl emerged from a mature sycamore tree alongside the creek just after sunset, entertained by our calls and flew in to investigate.

remarks: Time and date estimated; Early in the field season in 2010, as migrant birds were settling into their breeding territories, I recorded this newly settled great crested flycatcher 'singing' from a prominent perch. These vocalizations appeared as a song to me because of the cadence is steady and distinct, unlike the calls of great crested flycatchers I am more familiar with. This was the first time I became aware of the song of this non-melodic species. Great Crested bred on this territory later in the season.  Riparian deciduous forest; filtered noise 800 Hz and below

A murder of crows gathered in my neighbor's field and began calling. 45 degrees, sunny, light breeze. We hear crows often but what was unique about today was that one crow in particular was enjoying him/her-self by imitating a barred owl. This mimicry went on for over an hour. Topography: A running creek flanked by trees meanders thru hills and valleys with mixed open fields and mature tree stands. Recording was trimmed, amplified, and a fade in/out was added. Voice announcement in whispers by recordist as bird approaches nest on two subsequent visits, about 1.5 minutes apart. On the first visit the bird brought a small twig and on the second a piece of lichen, each placed in the interior of the nest. The cup is already formed but little to no lichen lines the outside yet as is typical in this species. Nest is saddled on a horizontal branch. (I need to return when leaves are more developed to identify the tree species).

Female calling from low in dense understory in deciduous woodland adjacent to a stream. remarks:
Found around 6:45am by Doreen Linzell and Dan Sanders, this bird continued calling (infrequently) until at least 11:15am.  I made this recording around 10am while the bird moved through the understory at or near ground level just west of where the Brookside Trail intersects the Hickory Ridge Trail at Blendon Woods Metro Park.  The bird continued calling for a few minutes after the end of this recording (out of storage space! Argh!) and around 10:15 or so hopped up on some dead branches while foraging allowing myself and a half-dozen or so other birders a chance to get a look at him.

This is a clip from the (8min) unedited track at http://soundcloud.com/paul-j-hurtado/kentucky-warbler-17june2012. Recorded at Blendon Woods metro park, Columbus OH on Sunday, 17 June 2012 around 11:45am using a Sennheiser ME67 shotgun mic and a Sony Hi-MD recorder, model MZ-RH910.  This individual was in a wooded area with some open canopy and sunlit groundcover. Lots of low woody shrubs and small saplings.  The bird stayed low (< 6 feet) in relatively thick vegetation, and moved approximately 40 feet through the bushes and understory during the recording period.  Presumably the bird was foraging. A singing male has been present in this area for a few weeks now, so this bird has at least attempted to nest in the area.  Insect noise and low frequency noisefiltered out using Audacity using a notch filter at 5.9kHz and a high pass filter cutoff around 1.6kHz.

The Canada Warbler was first seen and heard along a stream inside the wood lot, then moved to the edge of the wood lot while I ran back to my car to get recording equipment. There, it was mostly in honey suckle bushes or adjacent lower branches of trees along the edge of the wood lot.  I was pleasantly surprised to have a Mourning Warbler do the audio-equivalent of "photo bombing" my Canada Warbler recording!
